## YOUR TASK
When merging duplicate findings:
- keep the clearest title and body
- preserve the strongest concrete failure scenario
- choose the most critical priority among the merged findings unless the combined evidence says otherwise
- set confidence from the combined evidence quality; independent reviewers agreeing increases confidence
- extend the code location to the largest line range covering all merged findings;
  when merged findings span files, keep the location of the surviving finding
{{- if not .DisableSuggestions}}
- include suggestions from all duplicate findings, merge only when it makes sense
{{- end}}
- merge `verification` on duplicate findings:
  - merge the verification `remarks` if both have the same `verdict`;
    otherwise use the `remarks` of the finding with the highest `confidence_score`
  - set highest `confidence_score` of the merged findings
  - set the most critical verification `priority` of the merged findings
  - prefer the `verdict` of the finding with the highest `confidence_score`
  - `verification.id` must equal the output finding `id`
- always add the `id`, of the finding you merged, into `merged_from` of the surviving finding;
  findings kept unchanged need no `merged_from`
- account for every input `id`: it must survive as the `id` of an output finding or be listed
  in `merged_from` of the finding that absorbed it; no `id` may disappear
- DO NOT merge findings that you ARE SURE address different issues

DO NOT introduce new findings that no reviewer raised.

